{{italic title}}
[[Image:1862 Blacks Picturesque Guide to Yorkshire.png|thumb|right|Black's ''Guide to Yorkshire'', 1862]]
'''''Black's Guides''''' were travel [[guide book]]s published by the [[A & C Black|Adam and Charles Black]] firm of Edinburgh (later London) beginning in 1839.<ref name=memoir1885>{{Citation |publisher = A. and C. Black |publication-place = Edinburgh |editor=[[Alexander Nicolson]] |url = https://openlibrary.org/books/OL24355448M/Memoirs |title = Memoirs of Adam Black |publication-date = 1885 |edition=2nd }}</ref> The series' style tended towards the "colloquial, with fewer cultural pretensions" than its leading competitor ''[[Baedeker Guides]]''.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Local Modernity, Global Modernism: Bloomsbury and the Places of the Literary |author= Sara Blair |journal= English Literary History |volume= 71 |year=2004 }}</ref> Contributors included [[David T. Ansted]], Charles Bertram Black, and A.R. Hope Moncrieff.

