{{infobox dot-com company | name = Ideum | logo = Ideum.png | logo_size = 150px | company_type = Multitouch products and digital interactives | genre = | foundation = | founder = | location_city = Corrales, New Mexico | location_country = | location = | locations = | area_served = | key_people = | industry = | products = | services = | sexuality = | market cap = | revenue = | operating_income = | net_income = | owner = | num_employees = | parent = | divisions = | subsid = | company_slogan = | url = {{URL|http://www.ideum.com/}} | alexa = | screenshot = | caption = | website_type = | language = | advertising = | registration = | launch_date = | current_status = | footnotes = | intl = }}
'''Ideum''' is a company based in [[Corrales, New Mexico]] that produces multitouch tables and walls, custom interactive exhibits, and custom hardware. The company was founded in 1999 by Jim Spadaccini, who created interactive exhibits for San Francisco's [[Exploratorium]] before becoming creative director at Ideum.<ref name=bizjournal1>Kamerick, Megan. 11/18/2011. [http://www.bizjournals.com/albuquerque/print-edition/2011/11/18/ideums-touch-tables-bring-exhibits.html "Ideum's touch tables bring exhibits, displays to life"]</ref> With strong ties to the museum and informal science education fields, many of the company's products and services are targeted at museums and other public spaces. In 2015 and 2016, the company was listed on the [[Inc. 5000]], list of the Fastest Growing Companies in the US.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.inc.com/profile/ideum|title=Ideum: Corrales, New Mexico |website=Inc.com|access-date=2017-08-03}}</ref> In 2017, the company was honored as one of the "Best Entrepreneurial Companies in America" by Entrepreneur Magazine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.entrepreneur.com/360|title=The Best Entrepreneurial companies in America|website=entrepreneur.com|access-date=2017-12-26}}</ref>
The firm has a strong focus on developing interactive exhibits that seamlessly blend custom software, large scale hardware such as multitouch tables, and more recently new emerging technology such the use of fiducial markers and motion recognition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://issuu.com/trendmagnm/docs/trend_spring_2016_flipbook/35?e=0/35080469|title=TREND Spring 2016|website=Issuu|access-date=2016-06-13}}</ref> Ideum has also developed interactive video walls<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tech.co/ideum-uses-technology-educate-entertain-2017-01|title=New Mexico-Based Ideum Uses Technology to Educate and Entertain|website=Tech.co|access-date=2017-12-26}}</ref> and has created state-of-the-art installations using projection mapping.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.avinteractive.com/news/projection/christie-pandoras-box-makes-experimental-potters-happy-11-12-2017/|title= Christie Pandoras Box makes experimental potters happy|website=AV Magazine|access-date=2017-12-26}}</ref>
Ideum's first product, [[MT-50 Multitouch Table|MT-50 multitouch table]] garnered recognition for its high resolution and large surface.<ref>Davies, Chris. 2/5/2009. [http://www.slashgear.com/ideum-mt2-multitouch-table-beats-microsoft-surface-in-size-resolution-0533139/ "Ideum MT-2 Multitouch Table Beats Microsoft Surface in Size and Resolution."]</ref><ref>Instructables. 2011. [http://ideum.com/wp-content/themes/ideum2012/documents/Touch%20Products%20Comparison%20Chart_2013-05-10.pdf "DIY MT-50 Multitouch Table"]</ref> In 2011 and 2012, the company expanded its line to include three 55" multitouch tables, the Platform, Pro, and Pro Lab; two 46" tables, the Platform 46 full-sized and coffee tables; the Platform 32 coffee table; the 100" Pano table; and the 65" Presenter and Presenter 55 touch walls.<ref>Gerew, Gary. 6/29/2012. [http://www.bizjournals.com/albuquerque/print-edition/2012/06/29/ideum-takes-next-step-in-touch-screen.html "Ideum takes next step in touch screen technology"]</ref><ref>Fingas, Jon. 6/28/2012. [https://www.engadget.com/2012/06/28/ideum-unveils-speedy-platform-and-pro-multi-touch-tables/ "Ideum unveils speedy Platform and Pro multi-touch tables, says PixelSense ain't got nothin' (video)"]</ref><ref>Cooper, Daniel. 1/17/2012. [https://www.engadget.com/2012/01/17/ideums-mt65-presenter-a-17-500-65-inch-multi-touch-display/ "Ideum's MT65 Presenter: a $17,500, 65-inch, multi-touch display for your own museum"]</ref><ref>Ridden, Paul. 12/11/2012. [http://www.gizmag.com/ideum-launches-100inch-pano-touch-table/25403/ "Ideum breaks out 100-inch Pano Touch Table"]</ref> Ideum has continued to update and expand this line. The company was first to offer many of these touch tables with 4K and with 3M touch technology.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gizmag.com/ideum-55-inch-uhd-duet-coffee-table/43070/|title=4K multitouch coffee table supports "tangible" objects|website=www.gizmag.com|access-date=2016-06-13}}</ref>
These multitouch displays support Ideum's proprietary software development framework, GestureWorks which is written in C++. The free Open Exhibits SDK allows for the development of multitouch multiuser applications in [[ActionScript]] and more recently in partnership with [[Omeka]], development has begun in C++.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imls.gov/news-events/news-releases/federal-grants-30-million-awarded-support-museums-across-us|title=Federal Grants of $30 Million Awarded to Support Museums across the U.S. {{!}} Institute of Museum and Library Services|website=www.imls.gov|access-date=2016-06-13}}</ref><ref>2011. [http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/gestureworks-3-introduces-worlds-first-markup-language-for-multitouch-134753723.html "GestureWorks 3 Introduces World's First Markup Language for Multitouch"]</ref> Directed by Ideum, the Open Exhibits initiative was sponsored by the National Science Foundation.<ref>2010, 2012. [http://nsf.gov/awardsearch/showAward.do?AwardNumber=1010028 "NSF Award Abstract #1010028: Open Exhibits"]</ref>
Ideum has designed exhibits for the [http://www.cooperhewitt.org/ Smithsonian Cooper Hewitt Design Museum], [[NASA]], the [[Adventure Science Center]] in Nashville, [[California Science Center]], [[Monterey Bay Aquarium]], [[Miami Science Museum]], and the [[National Park Service]] among others.<ref name="bizjournal1" /><ref>2011. [http://www.digitalprojection.com/dp-case-studies/monterey-bay-aquarium/ "Interactive, immersive display with unparalleled image resolution at Monterey Bay Aquarium"]</ref><ref>9/2/2010. [http://www.miasci.org/blog/miami-science-museum-receives-500000-grant-from-noaa-for-interactive-climate-change-exhibit "Miami Science Museum Receives $500,000 Grant From NOAA for Interactive Climate Change Exhibit"]</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cooperhewitt.org/new-experience/designing-pen/|title=Designing The Pen {{!}} Cooper Hewitt, Smithsonian Design Museum|date=2014-07-15|website=Cooper Hewitt Smithsonian Design Museum|access-date=2016-06-13}}</ref>
